insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1998, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Stub Period DCF$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Run a DCF with a stub. Your valuation date is September 30, with a December fiscal year-end, so there is a one-quarter stub. The full-year unlevered free cash flow for the current year is 200, then 220 next year and 240 the year after, with a 3 percent terminal growth and a 10 percent WACC. Apply the mid-year convention. Roughly what is the enterprise value, and what does the terminal value contribute?$x$, $x$["Stub is 0.25 year, cash flow 0.25 x 200 = 50", "Mid-year discount of stub at t = 0.125, PV about 49", "Full years 220 and 240 centered at 0.75 and 1.75 midpoints", "Gordon TV on 240 x 1.03 / (0.10-0.03) about 3,530", "Discount TV at final-year midpoint 1.75, PV about 2,990", "EV about 3.45bn", "TV roughly 85 to 87 percent of EV - heavy terminal reliance"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First the stub. From September 30 to year-end is one quarter, so 0.25 of a year, and the stub cash flow is 0.25 times 200, which is 50. With mid-year convention I discount that stub at its midpoint, t equals 0.125, so it barely gets discounted - about 49. Then the full years sit after the stub, so the next fiscal year is centered at 0.75 and the following at 1.75, giving roughly 205 and 203 of present value on 220 and 240. For the terminal value I take the final-year cash flow of 240, grow it 3 percent and divide by WACC minus g, so 240 times 1.03 over 0.07, about 3,530. Under mid-year I discount that back at 1.75 as well, which is roughly 2,990. Adding the stub plus two full years plus the terminal, I get an enterprise value around 3.45 billion. The key takeaway is that the terminal value is close to 85 to 87 percent of the total, so the answer lives and dies on the terminal assumptions, and the stub and mid-year tweaks move it only at the margin.$x$),
(1999, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Recap Plus Bolt-On$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A sponsor buys a business at 8.0 times 100 of EBITDA, funding 320 of equity and 480 of debt. In year two they do a bolt-on, paying 6.0 times for 25 of EBITDA, funded with 120 of new debt and 30 of fresh sponsor equity. In year three a debt-funded dividend recap returns 100 to the sponsor. They exit in year five at 8.5 times on 140 of EBITDA, with 500 of net debt remaining. What is the money multiple and roughly the IRR, and how does the recap reshape the return?$x$, $x$["Exit EV 8.5 x 140 = 1,190, less 500 debt = 690 equity", "Sponsor cash out: 320 at t0 plus 30 at t2", "Cash in: 100 recap at t3 plus 690 at exit", "MoM about 790 in versus 350 out, about 2.3x", "IRR roughly high-teens, near 20 percent", "Recap pulls cash forward, lifts IRR via timing", "Bolt-on adds EBITDA cheaply, multiple arbitrage 6x in 8.5x out"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Let me track the sponsor cash flows. At entry they put in 320. In year two the bolt-on needs 30 of fresh equity, so that is another outflow. The bolt-on is bought at 6 times and folds into a business that exits at 8.5 times, so that is cheap multiple arbitrage on top of the added EBITDA. In year three the recap returns 100 to the sponsor - that is cash in hand without selling anything. At exit the EV is 8.5 times 140, or 1,190, less 500 of net debt, so 690 of equity proceeds. Total in is 320 plus 30, about 350; total out is 100 plus 690, about 790. So the money multiple is roughly 2.3 times. On timing, the stream is minus 320, minus 30 in year two, plus 100 in year three, plus 690 at year five, which solves to an IRR in the high teens, near 20 percent. The recap is the interesting part - taking 100 out early does not change the total dollars much, but pulling cash forward meaningfully lifts the IRR because money in year three is worth more than money in year five.$x$),
(2000, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$IRR Attribution Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Build me an IRR attribution bridge. A sponsor enters at 9.0 times on 150 of EBITDA with 900 of debt, so 450 of equity. Five years later they exit at 10.0 times on 210 of EBITDA, with debt paid down to 500. Decompose the equity value creation into EBITDA growth, multiple expansion, and debt paydown, and give me the money multiple and IRR.$x$, $x$["Entry equity 1,350 EV less 900 = 450", "Exit equity 2,100 EV less 500 = 1,600", "MoM 1,600/450 = 3.6x, IRR about 29 percent", "EBITDA growth: 60 x 9.0x entry multiple = 540", "Multiple expansion: 1.0 turn x 210 = 210", "Debt paydown: 900-500 = 400", "Three effects sum to 1,150 = total equity gain"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Start with the bookends. Entry EV is 9 times 150, or 1,350, less 900 of debt, so 450 of equity. Exit EV is 10 times 210, or 2,100, less 500 of debt, so 1,600 of equity. That is a 3.6 times money multiple over five years, which is roughly a 29 percent IRR. Now bridge the 1,150 of equity gain. For EBITDA growth I hold the entry multiple constant and apply it to the growth, so 60 of incremental EBITDA times 9 turns is 540. For multiple expansion I take the one turn of uplift on the exit EBITDA, so 1 times 210 is 210. For debt paydown, every dollar of debt retired flows straight to equity, so 900 down to 500 is 400. Add them up - 540 plus 210 plus 400 is exactly 1,150, which ties to the equity gain. The story here is that EBITDA growth did the heaviest lifting, deleveraging was a solid second, and multiple expansion was the smallest and least controllable piece - which is the honest way to underwrite.$x$),
(2001, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Pro-Forma EPS And Credit$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A merger-model output check. The acquirer has 200 of net income on 100 shares, 500 of EBITDA, and 1,000 of existing net debt. It buys a target for 1,800 of enterprise value entirely with new debt at 7 percent, 25 percent tax rate. The target adds 90 of net income and 200 of EBITDA. Give me the pro-forma EPS accretion or dilution and the key credit stats.$x$, $x$["Acquirer EPS = 200/100 = 2.00", "After-tax new interest = 1,800 x 7% x 0.75 = 94.5", "PF net income = 200 + 90 - 94.5 = 195.5", "No new shares, PF EPS 1.96 -> about 2 percent dilutive", "PF net debt 2,800, PF EBITDA 700, leverage 4.0x up from 2.0x", "Coverage needs an assumed rate on existing debt, say 6%", "Dilutive because debt yield exceeds target earnings yield"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Acquirer standalone EPS is 200 over 100 shares, so 2.00. Because this is all debt funded, there are no new shares, so it comes down to whether the target earnings cover the after-tax interest. New interest is 1,800 times 7 percent, or 126 pre-tax, and after a 25 percent shield that is about 94.5. Pro-forma net income is 200 plus the target 90 minus 94.5, so 195.5. Divide by the same 100 shares and EPS is about 1.96, so roughly 2 percent dilutive. The reason is simple - the after-tax cost of the new debt is about 5.25 percent, but the target only earns 90 on 1,800, an earnings yield of 5 percent, so you finance at slightly more than the asset earns. On credit, pro-forma net debt is 2,800 against 700 of EBITDA, so 4.0 times levered, up from 2.0 times. For coverage I need a rate on the existing 1,000 of debt - assume around 6 percent, so total cash interest is roughly 126 plus 60, or 186, and EBITDA over interest is about 3.8 times. So a modestly dilutive, materially more levered pro-forma - I would push for some equity or synergies.$x$),
(2002, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Distressed Debt-For-Equity Exchange$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$An out-of-court restructuring case. A company has 200 of EBITDA and a going-concern value of about 4.5 times, sitting behind 600 of secured term loan and 800 of unsecured bonds that trade at 25 cents. The sponsor proposes a debt-for-equity exchange: bondholders swap their 800 of face for 80 percent of the reorganized equity while the secured stays in place. As advisor to the bondholders, is this worth accepting, and what would you push for?$x$, $x$["Going-concern EV 4.5 x 200 = 900", "Secured 600 is money-good, residual equity 900-600 = 300", "Bonds get 80% of 300 = 240, about 30 cents on face", "Liquidation alt: fire-sale 650, less 600 secured = 50, about 6 cents", "Exchange 30c beats liquidation 6c and market 25c", "Accept only if you believe the going-concern multiple", "Negotiate: push above 80%, demand plan and governance rights"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I anchor the going-concern value. At 4.5 times 200 of EBITDA the enterprise is worth about 900. The secured term loan of 600 sits ahead and is money-good, so the residual equity value in a reorganized business is 900 minus 600, or 300. Under the exchange the bondholders swap their 800 of face for 80 percent of that reorganized equity, which is 240, or 30 cents on the dollar of face. Now the comparison. The bonds trade at only 25 cents in the distressed market, and if instead they forced a liquidation, a fire-sale of assets at say 650 would pay the secured 600 first and leave the bonds just 50, about 6 cents. So accepting the equity is worth roughly 30 cents versus 6 in liquidation and 25 in the market - the exchange is clearly the better outcome, provided you believe the going-concern multiple. My advice to the bondholders is to accept but negotiate the split - push for more than 80 percent given the old equity is out of the money, and condition it on a credible business plan and governance rights in the new entity.$x$),
(2003, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$SOTP Conglomerate Discount$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Quantify a conglomerate discount with a sum-of-the-parts. A diversified group has three segments: industrials at 300 of EBITDA on 9 times peers, healthcare at 150 on 14 times, and media at 100 on 7 times. Unallocated corporate costs are 40 of negative EBITDA, capitalized at a blended 9 times. Net debt is 1,200 and the equity currently trades at 3,150. What is the discount and what would you do with it?$x$, $x$["Industrials 2,700, healthcare 2,100, media 700", "Gross segment value 5,500", "Corporate drag -40 x 9 = -360, gross EV 5,140", "Less 1,200 net debt = 3,940 SOTP equity", "Discount = (3,940-3,150)/3,940 about 20 percent", "Roughly 790 of value trapped", "Catalysts: spin, carve-out, or sell the lowest-multiple unit"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I value each segment at its peer multiple. Industrials is 300 times 9, so 2,700. Healthcare is 150 times 14, so 2,100. Media is 100 times 7, so 700. That is 5,500 of gross segment value, but I have to capitalize the corporate overhead drag - 40 of negative EBITDA at a blended 9 times is minus 360. So gross enterprise value is about 5,140. Subtract 1,200 of net debt and the sum-of-the-parts equity value is 3,940. The market only gives it 3,150, so the conglomerate discount is roughly 790, or about 20 percent of the parts. The driver is usually that the high-multiple healthcare business is being dragged down by being bundled with lower-multiple media and industrials, plus the cost of complexity and the corporate overhead. To close it you need a catalyst - spin or carve out the healthcare unit so it can re-rate to its own 14 times, or divest the media business at 7 times and redeploy. Just naming the discount is not enough; the question is what structural action unlocks the trapped 790.$x$),
(2004, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Margin Of Safety$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A break-even and margin-of-safety case. A company sells a product at 80 with 30 of variable cost per unit and 6 million of annual fixed costs. It currently sells 160,000 units. Give me the break-even volume, the margin of safety, and the degree of operating leverage, and tell me what that combination signals.$x$, $x$["Contribution per unit = 80 - 30 = 50", "Break-even = 6,000,000 / 50 = 120,000 units", "Margin of safety = (160k-120k)/160k = 25 percent", "Operating profit = 8.0m contribution - 6.0m = 2.0m", "DOL = contribution / operating profit = 4.0x", "A 10 percent sales rise lifts profit about 40 percent", "High leverage cuts both ways - 25 percent cushion is thin"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Contribution per unit is price minus variable cost, so 80 minus 30 is 50. Break-even volume is fixed costs over contribution, 6 million divided by 50, which is 120,000 units. They are running at 160,000, so the margin of safety is the gap, 40,000 units over 160,000, or 25 percent - sales could fall a quarter before the company starts losing money at the operating line. Now operating leverage. At 160,000 units, total contribution is 8 million, less 6 million of fixed costs, so operating profit is 2 million. The degree of operating leverage is contribution over operating profit, 8 over 2, which is 4 times. That means a 10 percent change in sales swings operating profit by about 40 percent in the same direction. So the signal is a high fixed-cost, high-operating-leverage business with only a 25 percent cushion - great upside if volumes climb, but a relatively thin buffer, and any demand shock gets amplified four-to-one into profit. I would want that fixed-cost base flexed or the cushion widened before underwriting it aggressively.$x$),
(2005, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Cash From Working Capital$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A working-capital impact-on-cash case. A company has 1,200 of revenue and 800 of cost of goods. Today it runs 60 days of receivables, 90 days of inventory and 30 days of payables. Management launches a program to get to 45, 75 and 45 days respectively. Roughly how much cash does that release, and where does it come from?$x$, $x$["AR on revenue, inventory and AP on COGS", "Current NWC about 329, new NWC about 214", "One-time cash release about 115", "Cash conversion cycle 120 days to 75 days", "AR release about 49, inventory about 33, payables about 33", "It is a one-time release, not recurring earnings", "Watch customer and supplier strain from stretching terms"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I size each piece off the right base - receivables on revenue, inventory and payables on cost of goods. Today receivables are 60 over 365 times 1,200, about 197; inventory is 90 over 365 times 800, also about 197; payables are 30 over 365 times 800, about 66. So net working capital is roughly 329. After the program, receivables drop to about 148, inventory to about 164, and payables rise to about 99, so net working capital falls to about 214. The difference, roughly 115, is a one-time cash release. Breaking it down, collecting 15 days faster frees about 49, trimming 15 days of inventory frees about 33, and stretching payables 15 days frees another 33. The cash conversion cycle goes from 120 days to 75. Two cautions I would flag: this is a one-time release, not a recurring earnings improvement - once you reset the level, the cash stops coming. And stretching payables and squeezing receivables can strain suppliers and customers, so I would check it is operationally sustainable rather than just a quarter-end push.$x$),
(2006, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Leverage Capacity$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Size the debt capacity for a buyout. The business has 200 of EBITDA. Lenders cap total leverage at 5.5 times and senior at 4.0 times, and require minimum interest coverage of 2.5 times. Senior debt prices around 8 percent all-in and subordinated around 12 percent. How much debt can this actually support, and which constraint binds?$x$, $x$["Leverage cap: total 1,100, senior 800, sub 300", "At full leverage interest is 100, coverage only 2.0x", "2.0x fails the 2.5x minimum coverage test", "Coverage caps total interest at 200/2.5 = 80", "Senior 800 uses 64 of interest, leaving 16 budget", "Sub allowed about 16/12% = 133, total about 933", "Coverage binds - capacity roughly 4.7x not 5.5x"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Two sets of limits, and I check which one bites. On the leverage caps, 5.5 times 200 is 1,100 of total debt, with senior capped at 4.0 times, or 800, leaving 300 of subordinated. But I have to test coverage at that structure. Interest would be 800 at 8 percent, which is 64, plus 300 at 12 percent, which is 36, so 100 of total interest. EBITDA over interest is 200 over 100, just 2.0 times - that fails the 2.5 times minimum. So the leverage cap is not the binding constraint; coverage is. Working it the other way, 2.5 times coverage means interest cannot exceed 200 over 2.5, which is 80. The senior 800 already eats 64 of that, leaving only 16 of interest budget, which at 12 percent supports about 133 of sub. So realistic total capacity is roughly 800 plus 133, about 933, or 4.7 times - not the headline 5.5. The lesson is that in a higher-rate market the coverage test, not the leverage multiple, often sets the ceiling, because expensive debt burns through the interest budget well before you reach the stated leverage cap.$x$),
(2007, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Pre-Emptive Bid Decision$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You advise the board of a profitable industrial-services company. A strategic delivers a pre-emptive all-cash bid at a clearly attractive premium and gives the board 72 hours to grant exclusivity before it walks. There was no prior process. The board asks the obvious question: do we just take this, or do we risk it and run a full auction to find a higher price? Walk me through how you frame that trade-off for them.$x$, $x$["Bird In Hand Vs Price Discovery", "Premium Adequacy Vs Standalone Plan", "Auction Could Surface Higher Bid But Leak Risk", "Deal Certainty Speed Confidentiality Of Pre-Empt", "Go-Shop Or Fiduciary Out As Middle Ground", "Market-Check And Fairness Opinion For Defensibility", "Who Else Could Pay More Strategic Vs Sponsor"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would frame it as bird-in-hand certainty against the chance of a higher clearing price, and I would not let the 72-hour clock stampede the board. First, is the premium genuinely full versus our own standalone plan and where the stock could trade if we execute. If it is, the question becomes whether a broader process realistically surfaces a meaningfully higher bidder, and who that is - usually one or two other strategics or a large sponsor. A pre-empt buys speed and confidentiality and avoids a leak that could rattle customers and staff, but it forecloses price discovery. So I would push for a structural compromise: rather than blind exclusivity, negotiate the price up now, then protect optionality with a go-shop or at least a fiduciary out and a reasonable break fee, so we can still test the market post-signing. I would also run a quiet market check on a handful of logical buyers and stand behind a fairness opinion, so whatever the board decides is defensible. If the bid is truly above what any auction would yield, taking it is the right call - certainty has value.$x$),
(2008, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Divestiture Program Sequencing$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A diversified industrial parent has decided to exit four non-core business units over the next two years to refocus and pay down debt. As the advisor, they ask you not how to sell any one of them but in what order and over what timeline to run the whole program. Walk me through how you sequence a multi-asset divestiture program and what drives the order.$x$, $x$["Sequence By Readiness Marketability And Cycle Position", "Sell Cleanest Most-Separable Asset First To Build Momentum", "Stranded-Cost And Dis-Synergy Interdependencies Across Units", "Front-Load Proceeds Against Debt Maturities And Covenants", "Buyer-Universe Overlap And Market Capacity Avoid Flooding", "Carveout Readiness TSAs Standalone Financials Per Unit", "Tax And Basis Sequencing Signaling To The Street"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I treat it as a portfolio sequencing problem, not four separate sales. I would map each unit on three axes: how ready it is to be carved out, how marketable it is right now, and where it sits in its own cycle. Generally I sell the cleanest, most separable, highest-demand asset first - it builds momentum, validates the program with the Street, and brings in early proceeds. I would also look at interdependencies: shared IT, procurement and brand mean separating one unit can strand costs in another, so the order has to respect those links and the TSAs between them. Timing is driven by the balance sheet too - I front-load disposals that generate the cash we need against near-term maturities and covenant headroom. I am careful not to flood the same buyer universe at once; if two units appeal to the same sponsors, I space them. I would also weigh tax and basis, and the signaling - you want each sale to read as disciplined refocusing, not a fire sale. So the sequence is readiness, marketability and proceeds-timing balanced against separation interdependencies.$x$),
(2009, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Blocked Cross-Border Deal$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A signed cross-border acquisition of a domestic critical-infrastructure target has just been formally blocked by the national-security review authority - not delayed, blocked. Your client is the foreign buyer who has already announced. The CEO calls and asks, what now. Walk me through how you advise them on next steps and the realistic paths forward.$x$, $x$["Assess Whether Mitigation Or Remedy Can Salvage Deal", "Carve Out Sensitive Assets Or Take Minority Non-Control Stake", "Appeal Versus Re-File With Restructured Terms", "Reverse Break Fee And Cost Allocation Per Contract", "Walk Away Cleanly Versus Litigation Optics", "Reputational And Future-Deal Consequences In Jurisdiction", "Communications To Market Employees And Target Board"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I separate the legal reality from the panic - a formal block usually leaves a few doors open, and the worst move is reacting publicly before we know which. I would test whether the deal can be salvaged through mitigation: ring-fencing or divesting the sensitive assets, security agreements, local board control, or stepping down to a non-controlling minority stake that removes the national-security objection. If the authority's concern is narrow, a restructured re-file or an appeal may be viable; if it is a flat policy no, those are dead ends and I will say so. Then we go to the contract: who bears the regulatory risk, is there a reverse break fee owed to the target, and what are our cost obligations. I would generally counsel against litigating the government - the optics and the damage to future deal-making in that jurisdiction usually outweigh it. So the path is: can we remedy it, if not can we restructure to a form they will accept, and if not, walk away cleanly, settle the break fee, and manage the message to the market and the target's people. I would also debrief on what we misjudged in the original risk read.$x$),
(2010, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Pricing A Diligence Problem$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are advising a strategic buyer in a competitive auction. Late in diligence your team finds a real problem: a meaningful chunk of the target's recent revenue came from a customer contract that is up for renewal and may not renew, and management is downplaying it. You still want the asset. Walk me through how you price and structure around a diligence problem like this rather than just walking.$x$, $x$["Quantify At-Risk Revenue And Probability-Weight The Impact", "Adjust Underwriting EBITDA Not Just Headline Price", "Reflect In Bid Or Hold Headline And Claw Via Structure", "Earnout Or Holdback Tied To Renewal Contingency", "Reps Warranties And Specific Indemnity Or RWI Exclusion", "Use As Negotiating Leverage Without Tipping Whole Hand", "Walk-Away Threshold If Concentration Is Existential"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would resist two extremes - ignoring it to win, or walking from an asset I want. First I quantify it: how much revenue and EBITDA is genuinely at risk, and what is my honest probability the contract does not renew. I probability-weight that into my underwriting EBITDA, because the real adjustment belongs in the cash flows, not just a haircut to the headline. Then the structuring question: in a competitive auction I may not want to drop my headline number and lose, so I would try to hold price optically but claw the risk back through structure - a holdback or escrow released on renewal, or an earnout where part of consideration depends on that customer staying. I would also seek a specific indemnity or a tailored rep, since a known issue like this is usually excluded from standard RW insurance. Tactically, raising it sharpens my leverage on price and terms, but I would not reveal my full read of the downside. And I keep a walk-away line: if that one customer is existential to the thesis and cannot be de-risked, no structure saves it and I pass.$x$),
(2011, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Succession Versus Sale$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A founder owns a successful third-generation family manufacturing business outright. He is 68, two of his children work in the business but neither is an obvious leader, and he is torn between handing it down and selling to a sponsor or strategic. He asks you, candidly, how should I think about succession versus sale. Walk me through how you advise a family business at this fork.$x$, $x$["Separate Family Goals From Pure Value Maximization", "Management Depth And Genuine Successor Readiness", "Liquidity Diversification Versus Concentrated Family Wealth", "Sale Vs Partial Recap Vs Professionalize-And-Hold Spectrum", "Governance Independent Board And Non-Family CEO Option", "Tax And Estate Planning Generational Transfer", "Legacy Control Culture And Employee Considerations"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would start by separating the family's objectives from pure value maximization, because this is not only a financial decision. The honest first question is succession readiness - is either child, or an outside hire, genuinely capable of running this, or am I being asked to bless a handover the business cannot support. If there is no credible successor, holding can quietly destroy value. Then liquidity and risk: nearly all the family's wealth sits in one illiquid asset, and a full or partial sale diversifies that. But it is not binary. I would lay out a spectrum - a full sale, a partial recap that takes chips off the table while the family keeps control, or professionalizing the company with an independent board and a non-family CEO and holding longer. A sponsor minority can fund a liquidity event and bring in management muscle without fully exiting the legacy. I would bring estate and tax planning in early, since generational transfer has real structuring consequences. In the end I frame it around what he actually wants - liquidity, legacy, or control - because the right structure follows from that, not the other way round.$x$),
(2012, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Conflicted Management MBO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A public company's CEO and CFO are partnering with a sponsor to take the company private, and they will roll a large stake and keep their jobs. So management is effectively on both sides - they set the projections and they benefit from a low price. You advise the board. Walk me through the process safeguards you put in place and why they matter for a conflicted management buyout.$x$, $x$["Independent Special Committee With Own Advisors", "Management Walled Off From Price Negotiation", "Control The Projections Used For Fairness Analysis", "Go-Shop Or Active Market Check For Price Validation", "Majority-Of-Minority Shareholder Approval Condition", "MFW Framework To Earn Business-Judgment Review", "Disclosure Of Management Conflicts And Rollover Economics"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The core tension is that management sets the forecast and gains from a low price, so the whole job is to take price-setting out of their hands and make the process bulletproof. I would stand up an independent special committee of disinterested directors with its own legal and financial advisors, fully empowered to negotiate and to say no. Management gets walled off from the price negotiation - they can run the company, but they do not sit across from their own sponsor. I would scrutinize the projections hard, because a conflicted CEO has every incentive to sandbag the plan that underpins the fairness opinion; the committee should own the numbers used. To validate price I would run a market check or go-shop. Crucially, in the US I would structure to the MFW roadmap - condition the deal from the outset on both an independent committee and a non-waivable majority-of-the-minority vote - which shifts review to the deferential business-judgment standard rather than entire fairness. And I would disclose the rollover economics and conflicts in full. Those safeguards make the deal both fair and defensible if it is later challenged.$x$),
(2013, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Buyback Or Transformational M&A$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A mature, cash-generative company has built up a large war chest. The board is split: half want a sizable buyback to return capital and support the stock, the other half want to use the same firepower for a transformational acquisition that would reshape the business but carries real integration risk. As advisor, walk me through how you help them choose between a large buyback and a transformational deal.$x$, $x$["Buyback Is Low-Risk Per-Share Math Vs Strategic Reshaping", "Is The Stock Actually Undervalued For Buyback To Add Value", "Strategic Rationale And Durability Of The Target Asset", "Integration And Execution Risk Of Transformational Deal", "Return On Incremental Capital Vs Cost Of Equity", "Balance Sheet Capacity Optionality And Reversibility", "Signaling To Market And Shareholder Base Preferences"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I frame it as certain, low-risk per-share accretion against a riskier bet that could reshape the company's trajectory. A buyback is mechanical - it shrinks the share count and, if the stock is truly undervalued, creates real value per share, but it does nothing for competitive position and can mask a lack of growth ideas. A transformational acquisition can change the growth and margin profile entirely, but it carries integration, culture and execution risk, and most large deals that disappoint do so on integration. So I test the deal first: is the strategic rationale durable, is the asset one we cannot replicate organically, and does the return on that incremental capital clear our cost of equity with a margin of safety after realistic synergies. If it does, transformation usually beats a buyback because buybacks do not compound. If the rationale is thin or the price is full, returning capital is the disciplined choice. I would also weigh whether our own stock is genuinely cheap, our balance-sheet optionality, and what our shareholder base wants - a yield-oriented base reacts very differently to a bet-the-company deal.$x$),
(2014, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Defending The Fairness Opinion$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are presenting your fairness opinion to a special committee, and it is controversial: your value range sits below where some directors think the company is worth, and one director argues your comps and discount rate are too conservative and are being used to justify a low deal. Walk me through how you actually defend the opinion in that room without either caving or being dismissive.$x$, $x$["Anchor To Methodology And What Fairness Opinion Concludes", "Walk Through Comps Precedents And DCF Assumptions Transparently", "Show Sensitivity And Football Field Not A Point Estimate", "Distinguish Fair Range From Best-Achievable Price", "Address Discount Rate And Peer-Set Objections On Merits", "Acknowledge Judgment Defend It With Evidence", "Litigation Defensibility And Board Reliance"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would meet the challenge on the merits, not by retreating to authority. First I reset what the opinion concludes - that the consideration is within a range a reasonable seller would accept as fair, not that it is the highest conceivable price. Then I walk the committee transparently through the three lenses: the comps and why this peer set, the precedent transactions, and the DCF with its key assumptions. On the director's specific points, I take them seriously - if he thinks the discount rate is too high, I show how I built the WACC and run the sensitivity live so he sees what a lower rate does to the range, and the same for the comp set. I present a football field, not a single number, so the committee sees the spread and the judgment rather than false precision. I would distinguish the fair range from what the market might bear and remind them a market check is the real test of best price. Where there is genuine judgment, I own it and defend it with evidence. And I would be candid that this opinion must withstand a court and plaintiffs' experts later, so the assumptions need to be reasonable and documented, not stretched to fit a desired answer.$x$),
(2015, NULL, 'primary', $x$Case Study$x$, $x$Bear-Hug Response$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Your client's CEO receives a bear-hug letter: a rival has written privately to the board proposing to acquire the company at a meaningful premium, making clear it would prefer a friendly deal but is willing to go public or direct to shareholders. The board does not want to sell. Walk me through what a bear hug is and how you advise the board to respond.$x$, $x$["Bear Hug Defined Public-Pressure Friendly-Then-Hostile Bid", "Fiduciary Duty To Consider Not Obligation To Sell", "Buy Time Acknowledge Without Committing", "Evaluate Price Against Standalone Value And Plan", "Avoid Just Say No Optics Risk Of Shareholder Pressure", "Defensive Readiness Poison Pill Advisors On Standby", "Control The Disclosure And Communication Timeline"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A bear hug is a privately delivered acquisition proposal at a premium that is really a pressure tactic - the bidder signals it prefers a friendly deal but is ready to go public or straight to shareholders if the board stonewalls. The point is to box the board in, because once public, shareholders may demand engagement. My first message is that the board has a duty to consider a credible offer in good faith, but no obligation to sell - the two are different. I would not let them fire off a reflexive rejection; I would buy time with a measured acknowledgment that we will review it, while we assess the price against our standalone plan. If the offer genuinely undervalues us and we can make a credible independent case we can decline, but a flat just-say-no carries real risk if the stock has lagged and the premium is rich. In parallel I ready the defensive posture - confirm a pill is available, line up advisors, model what going public does to our shareholder base. And I would control the narrative with our own disclosure, so that if the bidder goes public we are not caught flat-footed.$x$);
